    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1955-09-09T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1955-09-09T00:00:00-05:00" n="67"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d67">
                <head>67. Letter From the <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                    the Deputy Representative on the United Nations Disarmament Commission
                        (<persName corresp="#p_SHE1" type="to">Stassen</persName>)<note n="1"
                        type="source" xml:id="d67fn1">Source: Department of State, Disarmament
                        Files: Lot 58 D 133, Inspection—Task Force. Confidential.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1955-09-09">
                            <hi rend="italic">September 9, 1955</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Dear <persName corresp="#p_SHE1">Harold</persName>
                    </hi>: This is in reference to our recent conversation<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d67fn2">No record of this conversation has been found in Department
                        of State files.</note> on the matter of the views of the Department of State
                    and the Department of Defense on the proposal for a Technical Exchange Panel,
                    which was the subject of the Secretary’s letter of September 1, 1955.<note n="3"
                        xml:id="d67fn3">
                        <ref target="#d66">
                            <hi rend="italic">Supra</hi>
                        </ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>We have now consulted with the Department of Defense on this matter and it is
                    agreed that the following express our combined views: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>The United States should propose in the Disarmament Subcommittee that
                            there be established a study group composed of technically and
                            scientifically qualified individuals from each of the countries
                            represented on the Subcommittee. This group would study inspection
                            methods and report back within a specified period of time to the
                            Subcommittee, such a group might be called a “Study Group on Inspection
                            and Reporting Techniques”.</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>No proposal should be made at this time for a Technical Panel which
                            involves exchange of visits and field testing of inspection methods at
                            actual installations.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <pb facs="0224" n="196" xml:id="pg_196"/>
                <p>In connection with the problem of providing the delegation with concerted
                    guidance, and to avoid your getting conflicting views during the Subcommittee
                    meetings, let me suggest that the Department of State should coordinate with the
                    other interested agencies in order that you may receive cleared government
                    positions.</p>
                <p>Sincerely yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_HHCJ1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Herbert Hoover, Jr.</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
